      "3 - 2√3:\n(2 + √3)(3 - 2√3)/[ (3 + 2√3)(3 - 2√3) ] = (6 - 4√3 + 3√3 - 6)/(9 - 12) = (-√3)/(-3) = √3/3 = 1/√3 = a 2`\n\nWait! \n\nSimilarly:\n`a 8 = 1/√3 = a 2`.\n\nNext, `a 9 = (a 7 + a 8)/(1 - a 7 a 8) = (-2 - √3 + 1/√3)/(1 - (-2 - √3)(1/√3))`.\n\nSimplify numerator:\n`-2 - √3 + 1/√3 = -2 - √3 + √3/3 = -2 - (3√3)/3 + √3/3 = -2 - (2√3)/3`.\n\nDenominator:\n`1 - (-2 - √3)(1/√3) = 1 + (2 + √3)/√3 = 1 + 2/√3 + 1 = 2 + 2/√3 = 2(1 + 1/√3)`.\n\nBut this seems messy. However, note that `a 7 = a 6`, and perhaps we can see that `a 9 = a 3`.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the sequence is periodic with period 6: `a 1 = 1, a 2 = 1/√3, a 3 = 2 + √3, a 4 = -2 - √3, a 5 = 0, a 6 = -2 - √3, a 7 = -2 - √3, ...`, but this doesn't match yet. \n\nBut earlier, `a 8 = a 2`, which suggests the period is 6:\nLet's try to compute `a 9` using `a 8 = a 2`, `a 7 = a 4` (as `a 7 = -2 - √3 = a 4`). \n\nWait, but for `a 9`, we have `n = 7`, so:\n`a 9 = (a 7 +",
      "we thought `a₆ = a₄`, so `a₇ = a₄`.\n   Hmm, no:\n   We have `a₃ = 2 + √3`, `a₄ = -2 - √3`, `a₅ = 0`, \n   then `a₆ = (a₄ + a₅)/(1 - a₄ a₅) = (-2 - √3)/1 = -2 - √3 = a₄`.\n   Next, `a₇ = (a₅ + a₆)/(1 - a₅ a₆) = (0 + (-2 - √3))/(1 - 0) = -2 - √3 = a₄ = a₆`.\n   So `a₆ = a₄`, `a₇ = a₄`. Hmm, but we can also calculate:\n   `a₈ = (a₆ + a₇)/(1 - a₆ a₇) = (a₄ + a₄)/(1 - a₄²) = 2a₄ / (1 - a₄²) = 2(-2 - √3)/(1 - (2 + √3)^2) = (-4 - 2√3)/(1 - (4 + 4√3 + 3)) = (-4 - 2√3)/(-6 - 4√3) = (4 + 2√3)/(6 + 4√3) = 2(2 + √3)/(2(3 + 2√3)) = (2 + √3)/(3 + 2√3) = (2 + √3)(3 - 2√3)/((3 + 2√3)(3 - 2√3)) = (6 - 4√3 + 3√3 - 6)/(9 - 12) = (-√3)/(-3) = √3/3 = 1/√3 = a₂`.\n\nThus:\n`a₆ = a₄`, `a₇ = a₄`, but `a₈ = a₂`. Let's check further:\n`a₉ = (a₇ + a₈)/(1 - a₇ a₈) = (a₄ + a₂)/(1 - a₄ a₂)`.\nBut previously, `a₃ = (a₁ + a₂)/(1 - a₁ a₂)` and `a₄ = (a₂ + a₃)/(1 - a₂ a₃)`, but here we have `(a₄ + a₂)/(1 - a₄ a₂)` which is not immediately relatable. Maybe better to compute numerically:\n`a₄ ≈ -3.732`, `a₂ ≈ 0.577`, so `(a₄ + a₂) ≈ -3.155`, `1 - a₄ a₂ ≈ 1 - (-2.154) ≈ 3.154`, so `a₉ ≈ -1`, but `a₁ = 1`. Wait, actually:\n`(a₄ + a₂) = -2 - √3 + 1/√3 = -2 - √3 + √3 / 3 = -2 - 2√3/3 ≈ -2 - 1.154 ≈ -3.154`.\n`1 - a₄ a₂ = 1 - (-2 - √3)/√3 = 1 + (2 + √3)/√3 = 1 + 2/√3 + 1 ≈ 2 + 1.154 ≈ 3.154`.\nThen `a₉ = (-2 - 2√3/3)/(2 + 2/√3) = (-6 - 2√3)/(6 + 2√3) = -2(3 + √3)/(2(3 + √3)) = -1`.\nIndeed, `a₉ = -1`. Now, `a₁₀ = (a₈ + a₉)/(1 - a₈ a₉) = (a₂ + (-1))/(1 - a₂ (-1)) = (1/√3 - 1)/(1 + 1/√3) = ((1 - √3)/√3)/((√3 + 1)/√3) = (1 - √3)/(√3 + 1) = (1 - √3)(√3 - 1)/((√3 + 1)(√3 - 1)) = (√3 - 1 - 3 + √3)/(3 - 1) = (2√3 - 4)/2 = √3 - 2 ≈ 1.732 - 2 ≈ -0.267`.\nThis does not yet seem periodic.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps there is a better approach. Let me try to define a new sequence `b_n = (a_n + i)/(1 - i a_n)` (where `i` is the imaginary unit) to use complex numbers. But this might be complicated in Lean.\n\nAlternatively, observe that if `a_n = tan(θ_n)`, then the recurrence becomes `tan(θ_{n+2}) = tan(θ_n + θ_{n+1})`, implying `θ_{n+2} ≡ θ_n + θ_{n+1} mod π`. \n\nThe initial conditions would give `θ₁ = π/4`, `θ₂ = π/6`, then:\n- `θ₃ ≡ π/4 + π/6 = 5π/12`,\n- `θ₄ ≡ π/6 + 5π/12 = 7π/12`,\n- `θ₅ ≡ 5π/12 + 7π/12 = 12π/12 = π ≡ 0 mod π`,\n   so `tan(θ₅) = 0`,",
