er terms. \n\nBut perhaps we should re-examine the calculation of `a₉` because we found a much simpler form. \n\nWe have `a₉ = -1`, and let's compute `a₁₀` again:\n\n`a₈ = a₂ = 1/√3`, `a₉ = -1`\n`a₁₀ = (a₈ + a₉)/(1 - a₈a₉) = (1/√3 - 1)/(1 - (1/√3)(-1)) = (1/√3 - 1)/(1 + 1/√3) = ( (1 - √3)/√3 ) / ( (√3 + 1)/√3 ) = (1 - √3)/(1 + √3)`.\n\nMultiply numerator and denominator by `√3 - 1`:\n\nNumerator: `(1 - √3)(√3 - 1) = √3 - 1 - 3 + √3 = 2√3 - 4`\n\nDenominator: `(1 + √3)(√3 - 1) = 3 - 1 = 2`\n\nThus, `a₁₀ = (2√3 - 4)/2 = √3 - 2 ≈ -0.2679`\n\n`a₁₁ = (a₉ + a₁₀)/(1 - a₉a₁₀) = (-1 + √3 - 2)/(1 - (-1)(√3 - 2)) = (√3 - 3)/(1 + √3 - 2) = (√3 - 3)/(√3 - 1)`\nMultiply numerator and denominator by `√3 + 1`:\nNumerator: `(√3 - 3)(√3 + 1) = 3 + √3 - 3√3 - 3 = -2√3`\nDenominator: `3 - 1 = 2`\nThus, `a₁₁ = -2√3/2 = -√3 ≈ -1.732`\n\n`a₁₂ = (a₁₀ + a₁₁)/(1 - a₁₀a₁₁) = (√3 - 2 - √3)/(1 - (√3 - 2)(-√3)) = (-2)/(1 - (-3 + 2√3)) = (-2)/(4 - 2√3)`\nFactor denominator: `(-2)/(2(2 - √3)) = -",
